{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","author_sig":"{\"payload\": \"\", \"payloadType\": \"application/vnd.rebar.authorship.v1+json\", \"signatures\": [{\"keyid\": \"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d\", \"sig\": \"\"}]}","data":{"fields":{"description":"## What\nAn OPTIONAL, isolated adapter that harvests coverage % and CI-health (run status, duration, red->green recovery, flake/recheck rate) from GitHub Actions run history and persists them as labeled snapshots into the going-forward store, so those trends stop depending on GHA's short log-retention window. The core command does not depend on this adapter.\n\n## Files\n- `src/rebar/metrics/adapters/github_actions.py` — new isolated adapter: parse a GHA run's coverage (anchored word-boundary grep for the pytest-cov `TOTAL` line in the run-log tail) and CI-health from run-metadata JSON (status/conclusion, duration, and — across a fail->pass pair — a red->green recovery interval; recheck/flake rate from repeated runs on one commit).\n- `scripts/harvest_gha.py` — new: pull recent `test.yml` run logs + run metadata (via `gh`/the Actions API), run them through the adapter, and append labeled snapshots to the snapshot store. This SCRIPT is the persistence path (run locally/by a maintainer), NOT the CI workflow.\n- `tests/unit/metrics/test_gha_adapter.py` — new.\n\n## Snapshot store path & why NOT the CI workflow\nSnapshots are written via `src/rebar/metrics/snapshot.py` to the git-tracked **`.rebar/metrics-snapshots.ndjson`** (the established store path — `reports/` is gitignored; do NOT use it). **The `.github/workflows/test.yml` is deliberately NOT edited to commit snapshots**: the CI workflow runs with `permissions: contents: read` and CI checkouts are ephemeral, so it cannot commit a file back to the repo, and committing from CI is out of scope and fragile. Instead the harvester reads coverage/CI-health from the GHA API/run-logs after the fact and writes the tracked snapshots itself — which is exactly what removes the dependency on the retention window. (The coverage `TOTAL` line is already emitted to the run log by the existing pytest-cov step, so no workflow change is needed for the harvester to read it.)\n\n## Approach\nCI runs on GitHub Actions; coverage is in the run-log tail and CI-health in the run metadata, but only within a short retention window — so the harvester captures that window into the durable `.rebar` store. To keep the harness portable, the GHA source is an isolated adapter the core command never imports; a parallel adapter could target another CI. Log parsing is anchored (word-boundary grep for the coverage `TOTAL` line). Emitted snapshots carry `source=\"snapshot\"` (or a CI-health-specific label) so they sit in the going-forward series. Additive and optional.\n\n## Tests\n- Unit (fixture log text + run-metadata JSON — no network): the adapter extracts the coverage % from a fixture log tail and computes a red->green recovery interval from two fixture runs; the emitted record carries the snapshot label. The core-command isolation is asserted by scanning the core module source for an adapter import.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] `tests/unit/metrics/test_gha_adapter.py` passes: a fixture `test.yml` coverage log yields the parsed coverage % (`assert pct == 84.2`) and two fixture runs (fail then pass) yield the expected red->green recovery duration.\n- [ ] `scripts/harvest_gha.py` writes the harvested coverage/CI-health as snapshots to `.rebar/metrics-snapshots.ndjson` (the tracked store), verified by a test feeding it fixture run data (adapter output stubbed/injected) and reading the snapshots back via `read_snapshots` — proving the persistence path and the correct store path (NOT `reports/`).\n- [ ] the portability guard holds: a unit test asserts the CORE metrics modules (`src/rebar/metrics/registry.py` and `src/rebar/metrics/__init__.py`) do not import the GHA adapter (and the future `_commands/metrics.py` from 9a5a is held to the same rule)."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784452076595677001,"uuid":"e311ecaa-acd6-47a9-a968-66768a25d811"}